^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|1D was fine. Now I have a bit of an issue. The hardest slams to bid are when both people have intermediate openers--16 points or so each. So, I decided to temporize and bid an inverted 2D. 2D is a one round force, and shows 10+ points. The upper range is unlimited. Partner may not pass 2D. Eddy is now supposed to bid suits with stoppers.  The question is, what should Eddy bid. If he is an optimist (and I like bidding optimists :)) he can decide QJ of hearts is a stopper and bid 2NT. Classically, most people would bid 2S, showing a spade stopper and denying a heart stopper. Given his flat hand and honors in hearts, I think 2N  has some merit. Once he bids 2N, I am sure we do not have slam. Why is that?|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Because, Eddy cannot have more than 14 points. He would have opened 1NT with 15-17 balanced.  If he had 18+, he would make some other forcing bid, as 2N can be passed by me. Hence even though I have 16, I know we have at most 30, so slam is not likely. It is barely possible we have a diamond slam, but I also have flat distribution, so that seems unlikely as well. The moral of this hand is, even if you have a good hand, once you realize slam is not likely, don't "fall in love" (at least with your hand). Just take your plus.|
