^-|CP||fp||at|^B@2^Y@31) If I make a minor raise (to either the 2 level or 3 level), I am guaranteed to have no 4-card major. |
PG| ***** 271 ***** |


AT|

2) I make a jump raise (to the 3 level) with 5 to a bad 9 points and a 5+ card suit. I might have the other minor, but feel that the jump raise is tactically the right thing to do to make it difficult for the opponents. I will tend to prefer the jump raise to a bid of 1N if I have 5-card support.|
PG| ***** 272 ***** |


AT| 

3) I make a limit raise with 10+ points and usually 5-card support. (The only time I will have 4-card support is if I am 4-4 in the minors and partner opens 1D.) If partner opens clubs, I will not have 4 diamonds. If partner opens diamonds, I will not have 5+ clubs (in SAYC; in 2 over 1,  1D/2C is slightly more complicated).|
PG| ***** 273 ***** |


AT| 

4) Opener should now respond with his lowest stopper. If responder has less than a game-forcing hand, he should continue to bid stoppers below three of the agreed upon suit, or 2N if he has ^*Iall the other suits stopped^*N. |
PG| ***** 274 ***** |


AT|

5) If responder has a game-forcing hand, he must make sure the partnership bids game by either bidding 3N, if all suits are stopped, or continue bidding new suits, if not. |
PG| ***** 275 ***** |


AT|

6) Similarly, if opener has 15+ points, it is his responsibility to make sure the partnership reaches game by either bidding 3N, if all suits are stopped, or continuing to bid new suits, if not. |
PG| ***** 276 ***** |


AT|

7)|FP|2|AT| Once 3 suits have been bid (the original suit and 2 stopper suits), if someone bids the fourth suit, that is asking about a stopper rather than telling, because if the bidder has the remaining suit stopped, he can bid NT himself. |FP||
PG| ***** 277 ***** |


AT|

8) Inverted minors are off in competition (including over takeout doubles), in the sense that a raise to 2 is less than a limit raise. A raise to 3 is still preemptive.|
